  "prompt": "Why does the sun rise in the east and set in the west but not the north and south?",
  "response": "The Sun appears to rise in the east and set in the west due to the Earth's rotation and its axial tilt. Here\u2019s a breakdown of the key reasons:\n\n### 1. **Earth's Rotation**\n   - The Earth rotates on its axis from west to east (counterclockwise when viewed from above the North Pole).\n   - This rotation makes the Sun (and other celestial objects) appear to move across the sky from east to west.\n   - As the Earth spins, different parts of the planet are exposed to sunlight, creating the cycle of day and night.\n\n### 2. **Earth's Axial Tilt**\n   - The Earth is tilted approximately **23.5 degrees** relative to its orbital plane around the Sun.\n   - This tilt causes the Sun\u2019s path across the sky to shift slightly north or south over the course of a year, depending on the season.\n   - However, this tilt does not change the fundamental east-to-west movement of the Sun.\n\n### 3. **General Direction of Rising and Setting**\n   - On average, the Sun rises near the east and sets near the west because the Earth\u2019s rotation axis is almost perpendicular to the plane of its orbit.\n   - Only during the equinoxes (around March 21 and September 23) does the Sun rise exactly due east and set exactly due west.\n\n### Explanation for North and South:\n   - The Sun does not rise in the north or south because the Earth\u2019s rotational axis is not aligned in those directions.\n   - In polar regions (near the Arctic or Antarctic Circles), the Sun can appear to move in unusual ways (e.g., staying above or below the horizon for extended periods), but this is due to the extreme effects of Earth\u2019s tilt, not a change in the east-west pattern.\n\nIn summary, the Sun\u2019s apparent east-to-west motion is a direct result of the Earth\u2019s west-to-east rotation. The north-south variation in the Sun\u2019s path is caused by Earth\u2019s axial tilt, but the primary direction of rising and setting remains east-west.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
